"# Chapter 10 — FX chain

The `composer/fx-chain` widget lets you build an ordered list of audio effects — reverb, delay, filter, chorus, distortion, bitcrush. The order matters: a filter after a reverb sounds different from a filter before a reverb. The chain records the order in the emitted form so the runtime processes signal in the sequence the kid arranged.

## 10.1 The verb signature

```
(composer/fx-chain :bind :available)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the fx chain writes.
- `:available` — list of symbols. The effects the widget will let the user add.

## 10.2 The emitted target form

An fx-chain writes its target as:

```
(fx-chain
  (fx/reverb :room 0.6 :wet 0.4)
  (fx/delay :time 0.25 :feedback 0.5)
  (fx/filter :type (quote lowpass) :cutoff 2000))
```

An ordered list of `(fx/... :kw val ...)` forms. Signal flows left-to-right: reverb first, then delay on the reverb output, then filter on the delayed output.

## 10.3 The widget declaration

```
(composer/fx-chain :bind (quote (synth :fx))
                   :available (quote (fx/reverb fx/delay fx/filter fx/distort)))
```

The available effects and the bind path. The current chain content lives in the target form the widget writes.

## 10.4 ASCII mockup — an fx chain

```
fx-chain: reverb -> delay -> filter

  fx/reverb :room 0.6 :wet 0.4
  fx/delay :time 0.25 :feedback 0.5
  fx/filter :type lowpass :cutoff 2000
```

Three effects in order. Add another with 'a', remove with 'r', reorder with 'm' up/down (per the v1.0 TUI spec).

## 10.5 The six effects (v2 direction)

The v2 audio design proposes six runtime primitives:

- `fx/reverb` — space simulation. `:room 0.0-1.0`, `:wet 0.0-1.0`, `:decay` in seconds.
- `fx/delay` — echo. `:time` in seconds or musical division, `:feedback 0.0-0.95`, `:wet 0.0-1.0`.
- `fx/filter` — spectral shaping. `:type 'lowpass|'highpass|'bandpass`, `:cutoff` in Hz, `:resonance 0.1-30`.
- `fx/chorus` — thickening. `:rate` in Hz, `:depth 0.0-1.0`, `:wet 0.0-1.0`.
- `fx/distortion` — harmonic destruction. `:drive 0.0-1.0`, `:tone 0.0-1.0`.
- `fx/bitcrush` — chiptune crush. `:bits 1-16`, `:rate` sample-rate divider.

The v1.0 widget accepts any symbol in `:available`; the runtime you plug into needs to know what to do with each.

## 10.6 Order matters — an example

Reverb-then-filter versus filter-then-reverb:

```
(fx-chain (fx/reverb :room 0.6 :wet 0.4)
          (fx/filter :type (quote lowpass) :cutoff 2000))
```

Reverb runs first (creating a lush tail), then the filter cuts high frequencies from the entire wet signal — including the reverb tail. Muted, distant sound.

```
(fx-chain (fx/filter :type (quote lowpass) :cutoff 2000)
          (fx/reverb :room 0.6 :wet 0.4))
```

Filter runs first (cutting highs from the dry signal), then reverb adds its natural high-frequency spread to what remains. Warmer sound with more sparkle in the tail.

Same effects. Different order. Different sound. The chain's ORDER is data.

## 10.7 A verified example

```scheme
(composer/fx-chain :bind '(synth :fx)
                   :available '(fx/reverb fx/delay fx/filter fx/distort))
```

Emit in a canvas:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (synth)))
  (composer/fx-chain :bind (quote (synth :fx))
                     :available (quote (fx/reverb fx/delay fx/filter fx/distort))))
```

The chain content itself (the ordered list of effect calls) is written to `(synth :fx)` when the user adds or reorders effects in the widget.

## 10.8 An fx-chain per instrument, or one per song

You can attach an fx-chain to an instrument (per-note effects) or to the master output (per-song effects). The composer doesn't care; you bind the widget to the appropriate path.

Per-instrument:

```
(instrument/define (quote lead)
  (synth :wave (quote saw)
         :env (adsr :a 0.02 :d 0.1 :s 0.6 :r 0.4)
         :fx (fx-chain (fx/filter :type (quote lowpass) :cutoff 2000))))
```

Per-song master:

```
(song :master-fx
  (fx-chain (fx/reverb :room 0.7 :wet 0.35)))
```

The widget writes wherever its `:bind` points. Both patterns work.

## 10.9 A canvas with an fx chain and controls

A common composer canvas pairs an fx-chain widget with sliders for the parameters of individual effects. The sliders don't write directly into the chain; they write into named slots the chain references.

Alternative: use one fx-chain widget only, and let the user tweak parameters via the widget's per-effect sub-controls (a v2 direction — v1.0 exposes chain add/remove/reorder but not per-effect editing in the widget itself).

## 10.10 What to remember from this chapter

- fx-chain holds an ordered list of effect calls and emits them as `(fx-chain (fx/... ) ...)`.
- Order matters. Signal flows left-to-right.
- `:available` tells the widget which effects to offer.
- Six effect primitives in the v2 audio design: reverb, delay, filter, chorus, distortion, bitcrush.
- Effects have their own parameter surfaces (per-fx keywords like `:room`, `:cutoff`, `:feedback`).
- fx-chain can attach per-instrument or per-song master; the bind path decides.

Chapter 11 introduces the text-field, color picker, and live-code widget — the round-trip window.
")
